Repeating my forecast. North Korea launched an ICBM today, probably either a Hwasong-15 or Hwasong-17, from reports I've seen. According to the text of the question, "the estimated range of a launched ICBM will be determined using data and reporting provided by the Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS)." This means that the question will resolve when CSIS publishes a news item that states which ICBM was launched, which will probably be tomorrow, although it could take a little longer than that. We need CSIS to determine which ICBM was launched, because that will determine the estimated range. In any case, Hwasong-15 and Hwasong-17 both have 10,000 km+ ranges, so this question is effectively done.

If my understanding of the data given for the Hwasong-14 ICBM is right, the missile has already a high end of potential range of 9 700km (some sources say 10 400km : https://allthingsnuclear.org/dwright/new-north-korean-icbm/) using the Earth rotation, and was tested in 2017 (https://www.38north.org/2017/07/jschilling071017/). The sources given here talk about "booster-glider" new types, but these can according to these same sources already be considered as ICBMs. Given the closeness of the 2017 figures to the end state of the question, and assuming "launch" means "initiated takeoff, with end data implying capacity", and that NK has been testing missiles several times per year every year since 2019, I think this is extremely likely.

North Korea Builds ICBM Base Near China as Fears of New Test Loom The location is meant to protect its most powerful weapons from pre-emptive strikes, allowing the military to expand an already rapidly growing arsenal. https://www.nytimes.com/2022/02/08/world/asia/north-korea-icbm-china.html

- Under Kim Jong-Un's rule (since 2011) there have been 3 ICBM (10k) launches, all in 2017. That's an average of around 0.27 ICBM launches per year. However, 2017 is the first time they were willing/able to do it, so the 0.27 number is not very useful. - The only ICBM capable missiles that they own are the Hwasong-13,14, and 15. - They have launched 9 missiles so far this year, a much higher rate than all previous years. One of those was a Hwasong-12, the first one fired since 2017. - In a Workers' Party meeting on Jan. 19, North Korea hinted that it was contemplating scrapping the regime's self-imposed moratorium on nuclear and longer range missile testing that has been in place since the end of 2017. - A Washington think tank said on Monday it has identified a military base close to North Korea's border with China that is likely intended for stationing ICBMs. - Launching an ICBM would definitely lead to even more sanctions. - There are 2 big 'celebratory events' this year that could coincide with launches, as has been the case historically.

Keeping my forecast based on the number of recent DPRK missile tests. Although short and medium-range tests, these tests and their frequency could mean the knowledge/results are being used to inform their scientific community about how to improve long-range capabilities. In addition, note the NYT article discussing a new ICBM base being build near the Chinese boarder with the DPRK. I speculate long-range ICBM tests are the intent of the base and therefore do not relax my expectations a test will happen before 1 Jan 2023, depending on how quickly the base is built.

Seven missile tests in the last month strongly signal Kim is yet again looking for economic concessions. Indications seem to point toward a looming North Korean humanitarian crisis in the wake of western economic sanctions, COVID-19, and closing its border with China. As a result, DPRK may continue to escalate until diplomatic preconditions that are in its favor are accepted. The latest IRBM test is a further indication of this approach. With that said, if North Korea warms to talks then continued escalation towards the 9000-11000km range may not occur.

Trump rhetoric with North Korea ratcheted up its nuke program, accelerating its desire to prove their ICBMs can range the US. Test conducted 2017 to present have not fully validated the capability. Medium and short-range missiles have been successful, but sustained pressure on a warhead in the atmosphere during a 10,000km journey has not been proven. Biden administration has been unsuccessful in reinvigorating talks, and the US keeps sanctions in place, so North Korea is likely working on a test sometime soon. within the next year, perhaps?
